  <body>
    <segment id="1">
The Truth</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="22" relname="span">

The Reichstag fire in 1933 and the war in Afghanistan - at first glance they seem to have nothing to do with each other.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> 

Some people may even be angry about reading the events in one breath.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="12" relname="preparation">

And yet,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="13" relname="span"> 

what people were told back then about the Reichstag fire was a lie.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="26" relname="span">  

Can we believe everything we are told today about the fight against terrorism in the Asian country?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="24" relname="span"> 

This war largely eludes even media observers.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="cause">  

What cannot be verified visually can be manipulated.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="23" relname="span">  

It can be portrayed as benefiting the interests of those in power.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="span">

The message of the authors of the play “One day we have to tell the truth” performed in Zossen on Saturday can be transferred to the present:</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> 

&quot;Be more sensitive and attentive, because we cannot be sure...&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="17" relname="interpretation"> 

No, we cannot be sure that we are being told the truth.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="19" relname="span"> 

We cannot be sure that our government will act in the interests of the people,</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="8" relname="concession"> 

even though the Chancellor has declared Germany&apos;s unconditional solidarity with America.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="evaluation-s">  

In any case, he didn&apos;t speak on my behalf.</segment>
